In [[Greek mythology]], '''Anchiale''' or '''Ankhiale''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: Ἀγχιάλη) was the name of the following personages: * Anchiale, according to [[Stephanus of Byzantium]], was said to have founded the town of [[Anchiale]] near [[Tarsus, Mersin|Tarsus]] in [[Cilicia]]. Her father was named Iapetus, and she had a son named Cydnus.<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0104:entry=anchiale-bio-1&highlight=anchiale Anchiale].</ref> * Anchiale, according to [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], was a [[Crete|Cretan]] [[nymph]], who gave birth to the [[Idaean Dactyls]] in the [[Dictaean cave]].<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0104:entry=anchiale-bio-1&highlight=anchiale Anchiale]; [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], [[Argonautica]] [https://archive.org/stream/argonautica00apoluoft#page/80/mode/2up 1.1130].</ref> * Anchiale, according to [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], was the mother of [[Oaxes]] by [[Apollo]].<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DO%3Aentry+group%3D1%3Aentry%3Doaxes-bio-1 "Oaxes"]; [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], ''Commentary on the Eclogues of Vergil'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2007.01.0091%3Apoem%3D1%3Acommline%3D65 1.65].</ref>
