{{Hinduism small}}
A '''Cultural Hindu''' is a religiously unobservant individual who identifies with [[Hinduism]], usually due to family background.<ref name="Fenton1988">{{cite book|last=Fenton|first=John Y.|title=Transplanting Religious Traditions: Asian Indians in America|year=1988|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|language=English|isbn=9780275926762|page=59|quote=The term "cultural Hindu" refers to Indians with a Hindu family background who have low observance of religious practices and whose identification with the Hindu religious tradition is primarily cultural or communal.}}</ref>

== Definition ==
[[Emory University]] professor John Y. Fenton defines the locution as follows:<ref name="Fenton1988"/>
{{quotation|The term "cultural Hindu" generally refers to [[Desi|Desis]] with a Hindu family background who have low observance of religious practices and whose identification with the Hindu religious tradition is primarily cultural or communal.<ref name="Fenton1988"/>}}

The term has come into vogue as a result of [[secularization]].<ref name="Beit-Hallahmi2014">{{cite book|last=Beit-Hallahmi|first=Benjamin|title=Psychological Perspectives on Religion and Religiosity|date=21 August 2014|publisher=Taylor & Francis|language=English |isbn=9781317610366|page=307|quote=Terms such as "cultural Christian," "cultural Moslem," or "cultural Hindu" express the reality of seculariztion, where labels imply family descent, but not any practices.}}</ref> Cultural Hindus, while not religiously devout, may still observe Hindu feasts, such as [[Diwali]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ochs.org.uk/sites/default/files/hindu-youth-research-project.pdf|title=The Hindu Youth Research Project|year=2001|publisher=The Oxford Center for Hindu Studies|language=English|accessdate=20 July 2017}}</ref> For these individuals, this commemoration of Hindu festivals, as well as occasional [[mandir|temple]] attendance, serve as a celebration of their heritage.<ref name="Brosius2012">{{cite book|last=Brosius|first=Christiane|title=India’s Middle Class: New Forms of Urban Leisure, Consumption and Prosperity|date=12 June 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|language=English|isbn=9781136704833|page=240}}</ref>

