'''Jethwa''' (or '''Jethva''', '''Jaitwa''', '''Jethi''' or '''Kamari''', '''Camari''', '''Kam(a)r''') is a branch of the [[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]] [[Rajput]] clan.{{cn|date=January 2018}}

==Origin==
[[File:Drapeau Porbandar.png|thumb|Merchant Navy flag of [[Porbandar State]] adopted by Jethwas, showing image of [[Hanuman]], from whom the Jethwas claim their descent.]]

It has been suggested that the [[Saindhava]] dynasty ruling eastern part of Saurashtra peninsula is now represented by the Jethwas. It is also suggested that the term Jethwa probably originating from Jayadratha (another name of Saindhawa dynasty), Jyeshtha (the elder branch) or Jyeshthuka from which the region derived its name Jyeshthukadesha.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Nanavati|first=J. M.|last2=Dhaky|first2=M. A.|author-link2=Madhusudan Dhaky|date=1969-01-01|title=The Maitraka and the Saindhava Temples of Gujarat|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.321094|journal=Artibus Asiae. Supplementum|volume=26|pages=83|doi=10.2307/1522666}}</ref>{{qn|date=January 2018}}<ref>{{cite journal |last= Kumar|first= Amit|year= 2012|title= Maritime History of India: An Overview|journal= Maritime Affairs:Journal of the National Maritime Foundation of India|publisher= Taylor & Francis|volume= 8|issue= 1|pages= 93–115|DOI= 10.1080/09733159.2012.690562|quote= "In 776 AD, Arabs tried to invade Sind again but were defeated by the Saindhava naval fleet. A Saindhava inscription provides information about these naval actions."}}</ref>{{qn|date=January 2018}}<ref name=SV>{{cite thesis |last=Vyas |first=Surendra |date=31 December 2001 |title=A study of ancient towns of Gujarat |type=PhD |chapter=10. Bhutaamblika |publisher= Department of Archaeology and Ancient History, [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]]|docket= |oclc= |url=http://hdl.handle.net/10603/72127|hdl=10603/72127 |pages=123-127|access-date=9 May 2017}}</ref>{{qn|date=January 2018}}<ref name="Majumdar1964">{{cite book|author=[[Ramesh Chandra Majumdar]]|title=Ancient India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bnZDAAAAYAAJ|year=1964|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|page=302}}</ref>{{Qn|date=January 2018}}

==Other details and Kuldevis==

The ''Jethwa'' [[Rajput]]s belong to the [[Gautama Maharishi|Gautam]]/Vajas [[Gotra]] and their [[Kuldevi]] is [[Vindhyavasini]] [[Devi]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=19MXTvyXK8WHrAevrNjPAQ&ct=result&id=nuPWAAAAMAAJ&dq=vindhyavasini+gujarat&q=vindhyavasini+jethva#search_anchor] Folk art and culture of Gujarat: guide to the collection of the Shreyas Folk Museum of Gujarat, 1980</ref> Jethwas also worship [[Brahmani]].<ref name=t>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=EzIZTozuJI-zrAfE-PjPAQ&ct=result&id=pQfgAAAAMAAJ&dq=harsiddhi++mata+jethwa&q=+jethwa#search_anchor] Fairs and Festivals of India: Chhattisgarh, Dadra and Nagar Haveli, Daman and Diu, Goa, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra</ref> Again there is one aspect of [[devi]], who is known as [[Jethwa Mata]], who is identified as ''Gaur Matas'' or clan deities.<ref name=t/>

