{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}} {{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Yengo | other_name = | photo = Mt Yengo.jpg | photo_size = 280 | photo_alt = | photo_caption = Mount Yengo | map = Australia New South Wales | map_alt = | map_caption = Location in [[New South Wales]] | map_relief = 1 | map_size = 280 | location = [[Hunter Region|Lower Hunter]] region, [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]] | label = | label_position = | elevation_m = 668 | elevation_ref = | prominence_m = | prominence_ref = | isolation_km = | isolation_ref = | parent_peak = | listing = | translation = | language = | pronunciation = | range = Calore Range, [[Great Dividing Range]] | coordinates = {{coord|32|58|54|S|150|51|04|E|type:mountain_region:AU-NSW_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title,inline}} | coordinates_ref = <ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR|id=SXjtoesEKW|title=Mount Yengo|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> | range_coordinates = | type = | age = | volcanic_arc = | volcanic_belt = | volcanic_field = | volcanic_arc/belt = | last_eruption = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = | normal_route = | access = }} '''Mount Yengo''' is a [[mountain]] that is located in the [[Hunter Region|Lower Hunter]] region of [[New South Wales]], in eastern [[Australia]]. The {{convert|668|m|adj=on}} mountain is part of the Calore Range, part of the [[Great Dividing Range]], and is situated within the [[Yengo National Park]], approximately {{convert|3|km}} east of the [[Macdonald River (St Albans)|Macdonald River]] and {{convert|17|km}} east by south of {{NSWcity|Putty}}.<ref name=gnb/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalparks.nsw.gov.au/yengo-national-park|title=Yengo National Park|work=[[National Parks and Wildlife Service (New South Wales)|NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service]]|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>
==Significance to indigenous Australians== Mount Yengo is a natural feature of spiritual and ceremonial importance to the [[Wonnarua]], [[Awabakal]], [[Worimi]] and [[Darkinjung]] [[Indigenous Australians]]. According to [[Dreamtime|indigenous mythology]], Mount Yengo is the place from which [[Baiame]], a creational ancestral hero, jumped back up to the spirit world after he had created all of the mountains, lakes, rivers and caves in the area. Baiame flattened the top of Mount Yengo when he jumped skyward and the flat top is still visible today.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/aboriginalplaces/MountYengo.htm|title=Atlas of Aboriginal Places: Mount Yengo|work=Office of Environment & Heritage|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wollombi.org/yengo.html|title=Mount Yengo|work=Wollombi Valley Arts Council. Communities Arts NSW|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=2014|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>
